          "type": "example",
          "title": "Computing a Linear Combination",
          "statement": "Compute the linear combination $2\\mathbf{v} + 3\\mathbf{w}$ where $\\mathbf{v} = (1, 2)$ and $\\mathbf{w} = (3, -1)$.",
          "solution": {
            "steps": [
              {"title": "Scale each vector", "content": "$2\\mathbf{v} = 2(1, 2) = (2, 4)$ and $3\\mathbf{w} = 3(3, -1) = (9, -3)$"},
              {"title": "Add the scaled vectors", "content": "$(2, 4) + (9, -3) = (2+9, 4-3) = (11, 1)$"}
            ],
            "conclusion": "$2\\mathbf{v} + 3\\mathbf{w} = (11, 1)$"
          }
        }
      ],
      "exercises": [
        {
          "id": "1-1-1",
          "type": "exercise",
          "number": "1.1.1",
          "statement": "Compute $3\\mathbf{u} - 2\\mathbf{v}$ where $\\mathbf{u} = (4, 1, -2)$ and $\\mathbf{v} = (1, 3, 5)$.",
          "solution": "$3\\mathbf{u} = (12, 3, -6)$ and $2\\mathbf{v} = (2, 6, 10)$. Thus $3\\mathbf{u} - 2\\mathbf{v} = (12-2, 3-6, -6-10) = (10, -3, -16)$."
        },
        {
          "id": "1-1-2",
          "type": "exercise",
          "number": "1.1.2",
          "statement": "Find scalars $c$ and $d$ such that $c(1, 2) + d(3, 1) = (5, 5)$.",
          "solution": "We need $c + 3d = 5$ and $2c + d = 5$. From the first equation, $c = 5 - 3d$. Substituting: $2(5-3d) + d = 5 \\Rightarrow 10 - 5d = 5 \\Rightarrow d = 1$. Then $c = 5 - 3(1) = 2$. Verify: $2(1,2) + 1(3,1) = (2,4) + (3,1) = (5,5)$. So $c = 2$, $d = 1$."
        },
        {
          "id": "1-1-3",
          "type": "exercise",
          "number": "1.1.3",
          "statement": "Describe geometrically all linear combinations of $\\mathbf{v} = (1, 1, 0)$ and $\\mathbf{w} = (0, 1, 1)$.",
          "solution": "The set of all linear combinations $c\\mathbf{v} + d\\mathbf{w}$ forms a plane through the origin in $\\mathbb{R}^3$. Since $\\mathbf{v}$ and $\\mathbf{w}$ are not parallel (neither is a scalar multiple of the other), they span a 2-dimensional subspace. The plane contains the origin, the line through $\\mathbf{v}$, and the line through $\\mathbf{w}$."
        }
      ]
